    "contenu": "The document features a recipe titled \"Tartare d'algues\" intended for four people. Below is a structured breakdown of the document:\n\n### Recipe: Tartare d'algues\n\n---\n\n**Servings:** 4 people  \n**Preparation Time:** 15 minutes  \n**Rest Time:** 30 minutes (includes drying of seaweed)\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 10 g of dry sea lettuce (or 30 to 40 g when fresh)\n- 10 g of wakame (or 30 to 40 g when fresh)\n- 5 g of dulse (or 25 to 30 g when fresh)\n- 1 shallot (about 20 g)\n- 1 tablespoon of capers in salt\n- ½ shallot (about 20 g)\n- 4 gherkins in vinegar\n- 1 point of a knife of mustard\n- 4 tablespoons of olive oil\n- Freshly ground pepper\n\n**Instructions:**\n1. Rehydrate the dry seaweeds. Desalinate fresh seaweeds by rinsing them thoroughly. Also rinse the capers and peel the shallot. Chop the seaweeds and shallot finely, squeezing out as much water as possible.\n2. In a blender, combine all ingredients except the oil and mustard. Mix until you get a smooth texture.\n3. Add the oil and mustard, then mix again until the mixture is well-emulsified. Taste and adjust seasoning if necessary.\n4. Store the tartare in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.\n\n**Chef’s Tip:**\n- If using salted capers, rinse them long and thoroughly to remove excess salt, which provides a balanced acidity for the tartare. Optionally, enhance with a bit of lemon or vinegar according to taste.\n- Avoid using kombu, as it might make the texture too thick.\n\n**Good to Know:**\n- This tartare is excellent as an appetizer on bread and can also be served with steamed vegetables or cooked leafy vegetables, making it a versatile dish.\n- For more about rehydrating dry seaweeds and desalinating fresh seaweeds, refer to page 99 and 97, respectively. \n\n--- \n\nThis recipe appears to be from a larger publication possibly oriented towards innovative or vegetarian dishes, indicated by the tab \"Les recettes\" and a category listing including \"Champignons / Cèpes / Algues.\""
