    "contenu": "### Analyzed Document Content\n\n**Title:** Chenin Blanc Pairings\n\n**Content Summary:**\n\n1. **With Fruit-Based Desserts:**\n   - **Description:** Late-harvest Chenin Blanc is recommended with fruit-based desserts, examples being apple tart with whipped cream and honey-infused mousse accompanied by ginger-scented pears and quince.\n\n2. **With Slightly Sweet Entrées and Appetizers:**\n   - **Description:** Suggested for dishes with subtle sweetness, such as Thai coconut curries and grilled chicken with Texas barbecue sauce.\n\n3. **With Cheese:**\n   - **Description:** Chenin Blanc pairs well with almost any type of cheese including those from cow, goat, or sheep.\n\n**When Chenin Blanc Isn't Good:**\n\n1. **Incorrect Style Matching:**\n   - **Explanation:** Suggests not choosing a young or moelleux style Chenin Blanc for a roast halibut with lemon-caper butter.\n\n2. **Too Fiery Dishes:**\n   - **Explanation:** Spicy dishes with cracked black pepper or chilis can overshadow the subtlety of dry Chenin Blanc.\n\n3. **Overly Sweet/Savory Dishes:**\n   - **Explanation:** Extremely sweet or savory dishes like those with bone-dry components may not mesh well with Chenin Blanc.\n\n4. **With Strong Flavors:**\n   - **Explanation:** Avoid pairing with intense dishes such as prime rib with heavy sauce, or foods like calves' liver due to their strong flavors.\n\n5. **Strong Ingredient Dishes:**\n   - **Explanation:** Elements such as chocolate, coffee, or mocha might overpower Chenin Blanc.\n\n**The Cheese Plate Recommendations:**\n\n```markdown\n| Type         | Cheese Example                                              | Description       |\n|--------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------|\n| Fresh        | Chèvre (many countries), fromage blanc (France), ricotta    | Dry, off-dry      |\n| Semi-soft    | Slightly aged chèvre (many countries), teleme (U.S.A)      | Dry               |\n| Soft-ripened | Boursault, Brie (France)                                    | Dry               |\n| Semi-hard    | Cantal (France), Iberico (Spain)                            | Sparkling         |\n| Hard         | Parmesan (Italy), aged Cheddar (U.K., U.S.A)                | Sparkling, dessert|\n| Blue         | Cambozola (Germany), Gorgonzola dolcelatte (Italy)         | Moelleux, dessert |\n| Washed-rind  | Taleggio (Italy), Morbier (France)                          | Dry, off-dry, sparkling |\n```\n\nThis list showcases various types of cheeses and their respective characteristics when paired with Chenin Blanc wine, reflecting the diversity and compatibility of the wine with different flavors and textures of cheese."
