    "contenu": "The document describes recipes and historical contexts related to two types of kvass: beet kvass and lettuce kvass.\n\n### Beet Kvass\n- **Preparation**:\n  - Chop a large beet or two small ones into ½-inch/1 cm cubes.\n  - Place the chopped beets in a quart jar.\n  - Cover the beets with water to mostly fill the jar.\n  - Add a pinch of salt and optional whey or other starters.\n  - Ferment the mixture for a few days, depending on temperature, ingredients, and personal flavor preference.\n  - Taste daily and once it develops a deep, dark color and pleasing strength, strain out the beets.\n  \n- **Usage**:\n  - Drink as a beverage.\n  - Use as a base for borscht.\n  - Lightly carbonate by transferring the liquid to a sealable vessel and allow it to sit at room temperature for another day.\n\n- **Health Benefits** (as suggested by Sally Fallon Morell):\n  - Excellent blood tonic.\n  - Promotes regularity.\n  - Aids digestion.\n  - Alkalinizes the blood.\n  - Cleanses the liver.\n  - Treats kidney stones and other ailments.\n\n### Lettuce Kvass\n- **Preparation Similarity**:\n  - Made similarly to beet kvass but replaces beets with chopped lettuce.\n\n- **Historical Context**:\n  - Interest in lettuce kvass was revived by Gail Singer from Winnipeg, Canada, who investigated her heritage and food culture shown by her Romanian Jewish immigrant grandparents and her father—known for making various pickles, including lettuce pickles.\n  - Singer, along with food historian Alexandra Grigorieva, found about 30 testimonials from other individuals who remembered lettuce kvass, predominantly part of Jewish culture.\n\n### Observations and Contributions\n- Grigorieva worked on collecting and charting testimonials about lettuce kvass, noting its cultural significance primarily within the Jewish community.\n- Gail Singer spearheaded this revival by researching and piecing together stories and recipes from the past concerning lettuce kvass through internet resources 