    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_63",
    "contenu": "The provided text discusses various types of fresh fermented milks and creams. Here's an overview of the content structured by headings and bullet points for clarity:\n\n### Frozen Yogurt\n- Became popular in the 1970s and '80s as a low-fat, \"healthy\" alternative to ice cream.\n- Essentially ice milk mixed with a small dose of yogurt; standard proportion is 4 to 1.\n- During mixing, yogurt bacteria may survive in large numbers or be largely eliminated.\n\n### Soured Creams and Buttermilk, Including Crème Fraîche\n#### General Background\n- Historically, butter was made by allowing raw milk to stand, skimming off the cream, and churning.\n- The process involves gravity separation of milk, where bacteria spontaneously in the milk and cream develop characteristic aromas and tartness.\n- Important microbes involved are species of *Lactococcus* and *Leuconostoc*, which thrive at moderate temperatures and are moderate acid-producers.\n\n#### Crème Fraîche\n- Described as thick, tart, and versatile; excellent with fresh fruits, caviar, etc., due to its high fat content.\n- Typically contains 30% fat and is pasteurized at moderate temperatures.\n- The product lives up to 15 days refrigerated or up to 30 days with a typical cream culture.\n- A distinctive crème fraîche variation in America is essentially the same as the French version, sometimes with added rennet for thickness and flavored with diacetyl-producing bacterial strains.\n\n##### Making Crème Fraîche in the Kitchen\n- Can be homemade using cultured buttermilk or sour cream with cream containing cream-culture bacteria, left at room temperature for 12 to 18 hours until thick.\n\n#### Sour Cream\n- A leaner version of crème fraîche with around 20% milk fat.\n- Requires sufficient protein to cook without curdling and is used to enrich dishes just before serving.\n- Known for a slightly grainy appearance and texture, predominantly used in central and eastern Europe.\n\nThis structured summary covers the key aspects of each type of product discussed in the text, including their preparation, characteristics, and culinary uses."
