    "source": "CALCULATING_DILUTION",
    "contenu": "Here is the structured content in markdown format from the document:\n\n# CALCULATING DILUTION\n\nAfter lots of testing, the author came up with an equation to estimate dilution from stirring and shaking that takes only initial alcohol content into consideration. It works well for the range of alcohol content in cocktails. Ignoring sugar content in these equations, alcohol by volume must be input as a decimal (22 percent would be 0.22) and dilution is returned as a decimal percent. Dilution measurements derived by measuring a series of cocktails and fitting them to a curve using Excel.\n\n**Equations for Dilution:**\n\n- Dilution of a stirred drink stirred quickly with 120 grams of ¼-inch cubes for 15 seconds: \n  - **Dilution ratio** = -1.21 x ABV^2 + 1.246 x ABV + 0.145\n- Dilution of a shaken drink shaken with 120 grams of ¼-inch cubes for 10 seconds: \n  - **Dilution ratio** = 1.567 x ABV^2 + 1.742 x ABV + 0.203\n\n# STRUCTURE OF DIFFERENT TYPES OF DRINKS\n\nThe guidelines for specific drink styles are based on the analysis of forty-five classic cocktails—built, stirred, shaken, and shaken with egg white—and ten carbonated and blender recipes of my own. In the chart here accompanying the recipe sheet, you can peruse all the values for yourself. All the numbers represent typical ranges, not hard-and-fast rules, and outliers in the typical ranges that are presented.\n\n## Built Drinks\nBuilt drinks are typically almost entirely liquor, so their alcohol by volume is very dependent on the strength of their base liquor. As sipping drinks served on a rock, built drinks must taste good over a range of dilutions. This range makes it impossible to come up with a sugar-to-acid ratio—the proper ratio would constantly change as dilution changed. As a result, built drinks typically contain little or no acid.\n\n### Recipe Example for Built Drink:\n- **Recipe volume:** 2⅓–2½ ounces (70–75 ml)\n- **Initial alcohol by volume:** 34–40%\n- **Initial sugar and acid content:** roughly 9.5 g/100 ml sugar, no acid\n- **Dilution:** roughly 24%\n- **Finished drink volume:** 2⅓–3⅓ ounces (88–93 ml)\n- **Finished alcohol by volume:** 27–32%\n- **Finished sugar and acid content:** roughly 7.6 g/100 ml sugar, no acid\n\n## Stirred Drinks\nStirred drinks usually have some acidity but are not tart. They have a wider range of alcohol levels than other drinks do."
