es traditional wine distinctions such as those from Australia, noted for high-quality fortified wines traditionally labeled using Sherry terms like Fino and Amontillado, although direct copying of these terms is now restricted.\n   \n5. **Safe Consumption**\n   - The last part briefly mentions the safe consumption of alcohol, acknowledging both its cultural acceptance in moderation and potential health risks when consumed excessively.\n\n### Notable Features:\n- **Structured Data:** An inferred table could outline the comparison of EU and Non-EU label features, noting key differences in labeling practices.\n- **Visual Elements:** There are images of wine labels that serve as examples of the concepts discussed.\n- **Referenced Sections:** Specific regulations related to the discussed topics are said to be elaborated in Section 3 of the book, indicating further detailed reading available beyond this introduction. \n\nThis breakdown helps in understanding the document's comprehensive dive into the intricacies of wine law and labeling, particularly in distinguishing between practices in European and non-European regions."
